[image alt: a screenshot from a certain Wikipedia article; the screenshot contains the entirety of a section titled "Trump campaign use":

Donald Trump played the Rolling Stones' recording of the song at campaign appearances during the 2016 Republican primaries and the presidential election, including his nationally televised acceptance speech at the Republican National Convention in July.[20] Although the campaign had attained a blanket licence from ASCAP,[21] after the convention, the band said publicly that they do not endorse Trump and requested that he cease all use of their songs immediately.[22] Despite the requests to stop, Trump continued using the song at campaign rallies before and after the 2016 election.[23] According to Jagger, the band considers the use of the song as a play-out at rallies to be "odd", given that it is a "sort of doomy ballad about drugs in Chelsea".[24] The Trump campaign continued to use the song during 2020, and after it was played to close his political rally in Tulsa, Oklahoma, on June 20, 2020,[25] Trump was again warned by the Stones not to use their music. They said they were working with the performing rights organisation, BMI to prevent unauthorised use.[26] The Trump campaign stopped using the song soon after and began playing "Y.M.C.A." by Village People to end his rallies instead.[27] As of 2025, the Trump administration has been playing both songs at political events.[28]]

a screenshot from a certain Wikipedia article; the screenshot contains the entirety of a section titled "Trump campaign use":

Donald Trump played the Rolling Stones' recording of the song at campaign appearances during the 2016 Republican primaries and the presidential election, including his nationally televised acceptance speech at the Republican National Convention in July.[20] Although the campaign had attained a blanket licence from ASCAP,[21] after the convention, the band said publicly that they do not endorse Trump and requested that he cease all use of their songs immediately.[22] Despite the requests to stop, Trump continued using the song at campaign rallies before and after the 2016 election.[23] According to Jagger, the band considers the use of the song as a play-out at rallies to be "odd", given that it is a "sort of doomy ballad about drugs in Chelsea".[24] The Trump campaign continued to use the song during 2020, and after it was played to close his political rally in Tulsa, Oklahoma, on June 20, 2020,[25] Trump was again warned by the Stones not to use their music. They said they were working with the performing rights organisation, BMI to prevent unauthorised use.[26] The Trump campaign stopped using the song soon after and began playing "Y.M.C.A." by Village People to end his rallies instead.[27] As of 2025, the Trump administration has been playing both songs at political events.[28]
